From 1864 to 1867, representatives of Nova Scotia, New 
Brunswick and the Province of Canada, with British support, 
worked together to establish a new country.

From 1864 to 1867, representatives of Nova Scotia, New 
Brunswick and the Province of Canada, with British support, 
worked together to establish a new country

The Dominion of Canada was officially born on July 1, 
1867.

King George V, who assigned Canada’s national colours (white and 
red) in 1921, the colours of our national flag today

Canada’s First Prime Minister
In 1867, Sir John Alexander Macdonald, a Father of 
Confederation, became Canada’s first Prime Minister.

Parliament has recognized January 
11 as Sir John A. Macdonald Day. His portrait is on the $10 bill.

Louis Riel- a defender of Métis rights and the 
father of Manitoba.

Sir Wilfrid Laurier became the first French-Canadian prime 
minister since Confederation and encouraged immigration to 
the West. His portrait is on the $5 bill
